SIMPLE: stench
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stench
<hw>Stench</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To stanch.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Harvey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stench</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stench
<hw>Stench</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>stenc</ets> a strong
smell, fr. <ets>stincan</ets>. See <er>Stink</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A smell; an odor.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Clouds of savory <qex>stench</qex> involve the sky.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An ill smell; an offensive odor; a stink.</def>
<rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stench trap</b></col>, <cd>a contrivance to prevent
stench or foul air from rising from the openings of sewers, drains,
etc.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stench</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stench
<hw>Stench</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>stencan</ets> to emit a
smell, fr. <ets>stincan</ets> to smell. See <er>Stench</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To cause to emit a disagreeable odor; to cause
to stink.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Young.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stenchy</ent>⟦br⟧
